title: NASA invita a hispanohablantes a enviar sus nombres en Europa Clipper
summary: La NASA ha lanzado un nuevo sitio web en español para invitar al público a enviar sus nombres a bordo de Europa Clipper, una misión que iniciará su viaje a la luna de Júpiter Europa en octubre de 2024. title: Japanese space robotics company GITAI raises $15 million
summary: Japanese startup GITAI has raised an additional $15 million to continue work on lunar robotics technologies, three months after raising $30 million.

title: Microsoft signs new partnership with AI and data analytics startup
summary: Microsoft announced Aug. 29 a five-year agreement to provide cloud-computing resources to Synthetaic, a startup that uses artificial intelligence to analyze data from space and air sensors.

title: SpiderOak demonstrates zero-trust software on ISS
summary: SpiderOak announced the successful demonstration of its OrbitSecure zero-trust cybersecurity software on the International Space Station.

title: TransAstra claims NASA contract for debris capture bag
summary: Space logistics startup TransAstra won a NASA contract to manufacture a bag to capture orbital debris.

title: Virgin Galactic’s president explains how VSS Unity is now flying frequently
summary: "I don't think I'll run out of people who are willing to fly the spaceship any time soon."

title: Benchmark wins AFRL award to develop thrusters for ASCENT
summary: Benchmark Space Systems won a $2.81 million U.S. Air Force Research Laboratory contract to continue development and testing of thrusters running on Advanced Spacecraft Energetic Non-Toxic, ASCENT, fuel.

title: Op-ed | Welcome to the Third Space Age
summary: As the commercial sector takes the lead on developing digital age technology and capabilities in this Third Space Age, the national security sector will become a demanding customer.

title: ULA delays NROL-107 launch, last Atlas NRO mission
summary: United Launch Alliance (ULA) has called off its Atlas V launch of the classified NROL-107 Silent Barker mission set for Tuesday. ULA noted that “out of an abundance of caution for personnel safety, a critical national security payload, and the approaching Tropical Storm Idalia,” the decision was made to return the rocket and payload to the vertical integration facility (VIF) at SLC-41.
